                      A Sweet, Sweet Summer: Why is White Sugar Bad For You?</p>

                      <p>We put it in coffee, get tempted by it in desserts, and hardly even know how often it’s added into savory processed foods. Sugar certainly makes life sweeter, but is it also the underlying villain in nutrition?
                      </p>
                      <p>There are plenty of reasons white, refined sugar will hurt you when you eat it. Some describe it as nothing short of a poison, while for others, it’s a compromise food to be eaten in moderation. Surprisingly, this site even deems sugar as not bad for you at all, just a source of carbohydrates, a “basic fuel for the body.” Perhaps that site is funded by the sugar companies…or the U.S. Government.</p>

                      <p>One of my goals in the Sweet, Sweet Summer series is to explore whether there really are “more natural” sweeteners and “healthier” sweeteners than refined white sugar. Before I tackle that big issue, which has intimidated me for a long time, I think it’s important to lay the foundation of why we’re even asking those questions.
                      </p>
                      <p><strong>Is White Sugar Bad for You?</strong>            </p>
                      <p>Because bad bacteria love to eat sugars, sugar can depress your immune system by fueling the bad guys, just as eating yogurt and other fermented foods help feed the “good guys” with probiotics.<br>
